    {
      "id": "Lc9FHCYKmocqFf9fSOFuc",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -2558.78922801828,
      "y": 2871.95433844346,
      "width": 1075.4393310546875,
      "height": 225,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b1p",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1129571178,
      "version": 820,
      "versionNonce": 142338550,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1770457948316,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "2. Download is also the same, where we will request the pre signed url and then download\ndirectly from blob storage\n\n3. Sharing has some intricasies into it yeah - we can store the share list for every file, but that way\nfor every file the permissions will have to be checked and it will result into a lot of reads for every user\n\nThe better approach for sharing a file with other is to have a separate db and for every user keep \ntrack of the file which is shared with him, so for every user we can fetch the list of file shared with him and \nthus it will be an efficient operation. ",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "2. Download is also the same, where we will request the pre signed url and then download\ndirectly from blob storage\n\n3. Sharing has some intricasies into it yeah - we can store the share list for every file, but that way\nfor every file the permissions will have to be checked and it will result into a lot of reads for every user\n\nThe better approach for sharing a file with other is to have a separate db and for every user keep \ntrack of the file which is shared with him, so for every user we can fetch the list of file shared with him and \nthus it will be an efficient operation. ",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "yfJyo5DefYaznhtv66Qxu",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -2504.844533437355,
      "y": 3342.317341040891,
      "width": 704.3994750976562,
      "height": 925,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b1q",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 710020726,
      "version": 1095,
      "versionNonce": 736479146,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1770485525932,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "How to handle bigger files\n-> UX is important for bigger file uploads\nwhich get decided by two things\n1. upload update\n2. resumable update\n\n-> there are many limitations why we cannot \nupload bigger files at a go\n\n1. timeout - webservers and client can timeout uploading \na file as big as 50 gb\nmaths - 50gb file in 100mbps internet connection \n50 * 10^3/100 sec = 500/60  \n\n2. browsers and servers limitation - \n3. Network interruptions\n4. User Experience\n\n\n-> To solve this, chunking can be used - break the files into small pieces\nand upload them one by one\nNeeds to be done on the client side\n\n-> How to handle resumable uploads\nneed to track the chunks which have been uploaded and \nwhich haven't been\n\nsaving the upload in the db\n\nid\nname\nsize\nmimeType\nuploadedBy\nStatus\nchunks: [{}, {}, {}]\n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "How to handle bigger files\n-> UX is important for bigger file uploads\nwhich get decided by two things\n1. upload update\n2. resumable update\n\n-> there are many limitations why we cannot \nupload bigger files at a go\n\n1. timeout - webservers and client can timeout uploading \na file as big as 50 gb\nmaths - 50gb file in 100mbps internet connection \n50 * 10^3/100 sec = 500/60  \n\n2. browsers and servers limitation - \n3. Network interruptions\n4. User Experience\n\n\n-> To solve this, chunking can be used - break the files into small pieces\nand upload them one by one\nNeeds to be done on the client side\n\n-> How to handle resumable uploads\nneed to track the chunks which have been uploaded and \nwhich haven't been\n\nsaving the upload in the db\n\nid\nname\nsize\nmimeType\nuploadedBy\nStatus\nchunks: [{}, {}, {}]\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "e2FK7EeAR8PuDWuB0x8iM",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -2510.7237150871556,
      "y": 4290.474176311295,
      "width": 869.619384765625,
      "height": 500,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b1r",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 844126838,
      "version": 1731,
      "versionNonce": 1820444202,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1770486187675,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "-> id, name, size, mimeType, uploadedBy, status, chunks\n\nHow do we keep the chunk in sync with the actual chunks that has been uploaded\n\nPatch request from the client - client takes the file, breaks it, upload the \nchunks directly to s3 and send a patch request to the server with the details\nof the chunk uploaded, issue is we are trusting the client to keep the chunks field\nupdated in the file metadata db, a malicious user can send a PATCH request to our \nbackend to mark all its chunks as uploaded without actually updating it to s3, although\nby this he will be able to corrupt his file only, but it still is an issue for , its still\na risk and create an inconsistent state that will be tough to debug. we can use a server\nside check to verify if the chunks field is getting updated with the correct and \nactual details of the chunks that are getting uploaded to s3\n\nserver side chunk verification - ETags, s3 notifications don't trigger for individual\nmultipart upload parts, we need to use S3's multipart upload api more directly\neach chunk gets an etag after successful upload to s3, which the client can include \nin the patch request to our backend, our backend can then verify these Etags by \ncalling s3's ListParts API, proving an efficient way to validate multipart chunks\nat once. balances user experience with data integrity",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "-> id, name, size, mimeType, uploadedBy, status, chunks\n\nHow do we keep the chunk in sync with the actual chunks that has been uploaded\n\nPatch request from the client - client takes the file, breaks it, upload the \nchunks directly to s3 and send a patch request to the server with the details\nof the chunk uploaded, issue is we are trusting the client to keep the chunks field\nupdated in the file metadata db, a malicious user can send a PATCH request to our \nbackend to mark all its chunks as uploaded without actually updating it to s3, although\nby this he will be able to corrupt his file only, but it still is an issue for , its still\na risk and create an inconsistent state that will be tough to debug. we can use a server\nside check to verify if the chunks field is getting updated with the correct and \nactual details of the chunks that are getting uploaded to s3\n\nserver side chunk verification - ETags, s3 notifications don't trigger for individual\nmultipart upload parts, we need to use S3's multipart upload api more directly\neach chunk gets an etag after successful upload to s3, which the client can include \nin the patch request to our backend, our backend can then verify these Etags by \ncalling s3's ListParts API, proving an efficient way to validate multipart chunks\nat once. balances user experience with data integrity",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "chpVqKE320sHNVjb_iwuU",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -2537.034120618016,
      "y": 4959.19194188289,
      "width": 886.9594116210938,
      "height": 175,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b1s",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 473768950,
      "version": 625,
      "versionNonce": 1257500662,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1770486432695,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "How to uniquely identify a file and a chunk - cant do it by filename, not even after\nappending the timestamp, to check if the file was already getting uploaded we need to \nfirst verify if we had initiated the upload before, and then we need to check the chunks\nthere, but we cannot check for the file by it's name, the same name can be used by other\nusers too, so for this we create a unique identifier for the file using its own content and \nthis is called a fingerprint.\n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "How to uniquely identify a file and a chunk - cant do it by filename, not even after\nappending the timestamp, to check if the file was already getting uploaded we need to \nfirst verify if we had initiated the upload before, and then we need to check the chunks\nthere, but we cannot check for the file by it's name, the same name can be used by other\nusers too, so for this we create a unique identifier for the file using its own content and \nthis is called a fingerprint.\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "yned3Z76EgVHH4E0_VYrU",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -2662.7603490224856,
      "y": -1402.7374273085318,
      "width": 734.4395751953125,
      "height": 325,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b1t",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1199347126,
      "version": 391,
      "versionNonce": 793059126,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1770531964838,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "News Aggregator\n\nFR:\n1. Show news from different sources in scrollable manner\n2. Should be able to scroll infinietly\n3.  Click and get redirected to the orignal publishers page\n\nNFR:\n1. Availability > Consistency\n2. Low latency feed updates\n3. Handle users upto 100 M and should be able to handle spikes upto 500M\n\n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "News Aggregator\n\nFR:\n1. Show news from different sources in scrollable manner\n2. Should be able to scroll infinietly\n3.  Click and get redirected to the orignal publishers page\n\nNFR:\n1. Availability > Consistency\n2. Low latency feed updates\n3. Handle users upto 100 M and should be able to handle spikes upto 500M\n\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
